Automatica

Volume 139, May 2022, 110188

Fully distributed observer-based consensus protocol: Adaptive dynamic event-triggered schemes☆

Author links open overlay panel
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.automatica.2022.110188Get rights and content

Abstract

This paper is intended to solve the fully distributed and observer-based consensus control problem of multi-agent systems with general linear dynamics under event-triggered communication (ETC). Two novel event-triggered strategies named adaptive dynamic event-triggered (ADET) schemes for one-to-all and one-to-one ETC are well developed, in which on-line triggering parameters associated with each node or edge and dynamic thresholds with updating laws are introduced, respectively. Firstly, an ADET consensus control protocol under one-to-all ETC is proposed and a sufficient condition for consensus is derived. Compared with most existing triggering rules, the on-line triggering parameter associated with each node makes the controller be designed in a fully distributed way. On the other hand, the proposed dynamic threshold has the potential of excluding Zeno behavior without sacrificing the system performance. Secondly, an ADET consensus control protocol under one-to-one ETC is studied, in which each agent asynchronously transmits its observer states to its neighbors depending on edge-based triggering functions. The one-to-one ETC provides a flexible self-regulated transmission mode. An effective fully distributed and observer-based consensus protocol is developed appropriately with available local measurement outputs, under which the agents are not required to have a priori knowledge of any global information. Further discussion on the efficiency of ADET strategies and comparison between state-based and observer-based ADET control are provided to enrich the distributed resources-aware control framework. Finally, one simulation example is provided to illustrate the theoretical results.

1. Introduction

Event-triggered (ET) control, which provides a deliberate, opportunistic aperiodic sampling/control scheme, has received increasing interests in the study of cooperative control of multi-agent systems in the past few decades (Dimarogonas et al., 2012, Ding et al., 2018, Guo et al., 2014, He, Luo et al., 2020, Heemels et al., 2012, Hu et al., 2016, Li et al., 2014, Li et al., 2015, Meng and Chen, 2013, Nowzari et al., 2019, Tabuada, 2007, Xu et al., 2020). In contrast to traditional continuous (or periodic) communication/control (Altafini, 2013, Li et al., 2013, Olfati-Saber et al., 2007, Ren, 2008, Wang et al., 2020, Yang et al., 2019b), a remarkable feature of an ET strategy is that sampling actions and control updates are determined by well-designed triggering rules, which effectively mitigates the communication burden and prolongs the lifetime of battery-powered agents.

Extensive research efforts have been devoted to solving ET consensus problems for multi-agent systems since the pioneering work in Dimarogonas et al. (2012). A large number of ET strategies have been established from various perspectives, see Cheng and Li, 2019a, Fan et al., 2015, Hu et al., 2016, Li et al., 2014, Li et al., 2015, Li et al., 2015, Meng and Chen, 2013, Nowzari et al., 2019, Senejohnny et al., 2018, Wei et al., 2020, Xu et al., 2019, Xu et al., 2020, Yi, Yang et al., 2019 and Zhu et al. (2017). For example, model-based and combinational-measurement distributed ET strategies for single-/double-integrator multi-agent systems have been proposed in Garcia and Antsaklis, 2013, Li et al., 2015, Meng and Chen, 2013 and Senejohnny et al. (2018). Leader-following/leaderless consensus problems have been addressed in Fan et al., 2015, Hu et al., 2016 and Xu et al. (2019) by designing appropriate ETC schemes. Note that the majority of ET strategies in the existing literature are static, in which triggering parameters and thresholds are constants.

Recently, by introducing an internal dynamic variable, dynamic ET schemes have been proposed (Dolk et al., 2017, Du et al., 2018, Ge and Han, 2017, Girard, 2015, He, Xu et al., 2020, Li et al., 2020, Yi, Liu et al., 2019). It has been pointed out in Dolk et al., 2017, Girard, 2015 and Ding et al. (2018) that the dynamic ET strategies have the potential of reducing more redundant transmissions without sacrificing the system performance, as well as the superiority of eliminating Zeno behavior, when compared with static ones. For single-integrator multi-agent systems, effective distributed dynamic ET strategy and self-triggered strategy have been established to guarantee asymptotic average consensus (Yi, Liu et al., 2019). A resilient distributed dynamic ET strategy subject to DoS attacks has been proposed in Xu et al. (2020). Extension to general linear multi-agent systems has been done in Du et al., 2018, Ge and Han, 2017 and He, Xu et al. (2020). For instance, effective distributed dynamic ET strategies have been proposed for solving a leader-following consensus problem (Du et al., 2018) or a formulation control problem (Ge & Han, 2017), respectively. Both leaderless and leader-following consensus have been studied in He, Xu et al. (2020) by designing a proper dynamic ET consensus controller. It is worth noting that, in the aforementioned ET strategies, some global information, such as eigenvalues of the Laplacian matrix associated with the communication graph is required to be known for the consensus protocol design, which brings limitations on the developed approaches. On the one hand, each agent has to know the entire communication graph to compute eigenvalues. Furthermore, calculating eigenvalues (or algebraic connectivity) of a matrix is a complicated task, which would take up lots of energy to process especially for a large-scale networks. It is unrealistic for the intelligent agent, which is equipped with an embedded microprocessor, but with the limited processing power. On the other hand, the scalability meets great challenge when some agents are removed or a link is destroyed. Re-design is required in the scenario. Therefore, developing a fully distributed dynamic ET strategies without using any global information is in great demand. Some initial results have recently appeared on this aspect (Cheng and Li, 2019a, Yi, Liu et al., 2019). Moreover, approaches in Cheng and Li, 2019b, Du et al., 2018, Guo et al., 2014, He, Xu et al., 2020 and Senejohnny et al. (2018) are based on static state feedback which requires the availability of full state information. However, it is rare in practice that the full state for each agent is available. Thus, designing an efficient dynamic ET strategy based on only local output measurements and further providing a comprehensive analysis on the relationship between local information and overall performance stand out as one motivation of the current study.

It has been emphasized in a recent survey (Ding et al., 2018) that to design a fully distributed dynamic ET strategy for addressing asymptotic consensus is of vital importance and still awaits a breakthrough. This paper is intended to move on in this direction, but not limited in agents with synchronous communication, discussed in the aforementioned literature (Dimarogonas et al., 2012, Xu et al., 2019, Zhang et al., 2014), in which agents synchronously transmit their information to all of their neighbors only if their common condition is triggered. Such ETC based on the synchronous information transmission is referred to as all-to-all mode in this paper. There is another similar ETC, named node-based ETC, which has been developed in Cheng and Li, 2019b, Dimarogonas et al., 2012, Li et al., 2014, Meng and Chen, 2013, Xu et al., 2020 and Zhu et al. (2017). Under the node-based ETC, each agent transmits its information synchronously for all of its neighbors, only if the agent’s own triggering condition is satisfied. This kind of ETC is called as either one-to-all mode or synchronous ETC in this paper, which has been commonly adopted in Cheng and Li, 2019b, Li et al., 2014, Meng and Chen, 2013, Wei et al., 2020 and Yi, Liu et al. (2019). A networked configuration typically has the advantage of information sharing, energy saving and flexibility. Note that the open network setting gives rise to some security issues suffering from cyber-attacks, which may destroy the interconnections among agents. In such a case, synchronous ETC may fail to flexibly adjust the transmission specially for those attacked communication channels without affecting the unattacked ones. A seemingly natural idea to this challenging problem is to develop an asynchronous ETC, which allows each agent asynchronously sends its information to its neighbors, that is, extending one-to-all ETC to one-to-one ETC. Unfortunately, this extension appears to be a non-trivial task due to the mathematical difficulties stemming from the extremely complicated dynamics evolution with multiple time scales. Different from the traditional edge-based ETC under which two agents linked by an edge simultaneously exchange data with each other (Cao et al., 2015, Xiao et al., 2012, Xu et al., 2017), the one-to-one ETC allows asynchronous information transmission between any two linked agents. Meanwhile, under the one-to-one ETC, the event condition from agent i to j is different from that from agent i to k. In such a way, an asynchronous data transmission is formed, which coincides with the distributed feature of multi-agent systems. Designing a fully distributed and output-based asynchronous dynamic ETC strategy stands out as another motivation of the current study.

Motivated by the above discussions, this paper aims at developing a novel systematic design methodology for fully distributed and output-based dynamic ETC strategies in both synchronous (one-to-all mode) and asynchronous cases (one-to-one mode), respectively. A prior knowledge of any global information, such as algebraic connectivity of graph, is not required. Firstly, an observer associated with each agent is introduced based on the measurement output. Secondly, an adaptive dynamic event-triggered (ADET) strategy is developed for a class of general linear multi-agent systems based on local observers. An adaptive updating law of the triggering parameter associated with each agent is designed, which plays the key role in a fully distributed design for the one-to-all case. Thirdly, the ADET strategy in the one-to-one case is discussed. The triggering condition associated with each edge is designed. Both one-to-all ETC and one-to-one ETC are taken into account in a unified framework so as to reflect a general fully distributed design for the dynamic ETC strategy. Finally, one example and some comparisons are given to show the effectiveness of the theoretical results.

Notation: The notation used here is fairly standard except where otherwise stated. N+ (N) denotes the set of positive (non-negative) integers, Rn and Rn×m denote the n-dimensional Euclidean space and n×m real matrices, respectively. Let In (I) mean, respectively, the identity matrix with n×n dimension (appropriate dimension). Furthermore, the matrix M>0 means a positive-definite matrix, and 1 denotes a column vector with appropriate dimension, in which all elements are one. A⊗B means the Kronecker product of matrices A and B. The right-hand Dini derivative of the function f at x0 is denoted by D+f(x0)≔limx→x0+supf(x)−f(x0)x−x0.

2. Preliminaries and problem statement

In this section, we recall some definitions and lemmas from algebraic graph theory and present the mathematical model of multi-agent systems so as to lay the groundwork for the analysis in the rest of the paper.

2.1. Preliminaries

A multi-agent system consists of N agents which communicate via a network described by an undirected graph G=(V,E) with a node set V={1,2,…,N} and an edge set E⊆V×V. Let A=[aij]∈RN×N be the adjacency matrix with nonnegative adjacency element aij. The element aij=1 if and only if (i,j)∈E; otherwise, aij=0. The neighborhood of agent i is represented by Ni={j:(i,j)∈E}. An element of Ni is called a neighbor of agent i and the total number of elements in Ni is denoted by di=|Ni|. In addition, self-edges (i,i) are not allowed, i.e. (i,i)∉E for ∀ i∈V.

Moreover, a path from agents i to j is a sequence of edges (i,j1), (j1,j2), …, (jm,j) in the graph G with distinct agents jk, k=1,2,…,m. Graph G is connected if and only if there exists a path from agents i to j for ∀i,j∈V. Then, let L=[lij]∈RN×N be the Laplace matrix with lij=−aij, i≠j and lii=∑j∈Niaij. The eigenvalues of L is denoted by λi with 0=λ1≤λ2≤⋯≤λN.

Lemma 1

Horn & Johnson, 2012

If the graph G is undirected and connected, then the corresponding Laplacian matrix L has a simple eigenvalue 0 and all the other eigenvalues are positive, i.e. λ1=0 and λi>0, i=2,3,…,N. In addition, λ2=minx≠0,1⊤x=0x⊤Lxx⊤x.

Assumption 1

The communication graph G is undirected and connected.

2.2. Mathematical model of the multi-agent system

Consider a continuous-time linear multi-agent system consisting of N agents, in which the dynamics of agent i (i=1,2,…,N) is described by (1)ẋi(t)=Axi(t)+Bui(t)yi(t)=Cxi(t)where xi(t)∈Rn is the state, ui(t)∈Rm is the consensus protocol, and yi(t)∈Rq is the output measurement at time t. A, B and C are constant matrices with appropriate dimensions, and the pair (A,B) is stabilizable and (A,C) is detectable.

Since only output measurements are available, an observer is designed associated with each agent to estimate the state, which is governed by (2)v̇i(t)=Avi(t)+Bui(t)+F(Cvi(t)−yi(t))where vi(t) is the state of the observer embedded in agent i, the matrices A, B, C are defined in (1) and F∈Rn×q is the feedback gain matrix to be determined.

Throughout this paper, asymptotic consensus is discussed, which is defined as follows.

Definition 2

The multi-agent system (1) with general linear dynamics is said to achieve asymptotic consensus if for any initial value xi(t0)∈Rn limt→∞‖xi(t)−xj(t)‖=0,∀i,j=1,2,…,N.

In this paper, fully distributed and observer-based dynamic ETC strategies in both one-to-all and one-to-one cases will be established. The objective of this paper includes

•

developing a novel systematic design methodology for the ADET strategy with only local observers’ information.

•

building a unified framework for both one-to-all and one-to-one ETC, under which we establish a fully distributed adaptive consensus protocol ensuring asymptotic consensus under the ADET strategy.

3. One-to-all ETC scheme

In this section, the one-to-all communication scenario is considered, where each agent synchronously transmits its information to all of its neighbors. A fully distributed and observer-based ETC is introduced and a sufficient condition ensuring asymptotic consensus is derived. The exclusion of Zeno behavior is also included.

3.1. The ADET strategy for one-to-all ETC

In order to characterize the one-to-all ETC, a triggering time sequence of agent i is denoted by 0=t0i<t1i<⋯<tsi<⋯. The observer error of agent i is defined as (3)ei(t)≜ṽi(t)−vi(t),t∈[tki,tk+1i)where ṽi(t)≜eA(t−tki)vi(tki). An ET function Hi(⋅,⋅,{⋯}︸di):Rn×R×Rn×⋯×Rn︸di→R is defined as follows (4)Hi(ei(t),ci(t),{ηˆij(t):j∈Ni})=γici(t)ei⊤(t)Γei(t)−ιi∑j=1Naijηˆij⊤(t)Γηˆij(t) where ηˆij(t)=ṽi(t)−ṽj(t), γi, ιi are positive scalars and Γ∈Rn×n is a constant matrix to be determined. In addition, the coupling weight ci(t)=∑j=1Naijcij(t) is time-varying with the following updating law (5)ċij(t)=πijaijṽj(t)−ṽi(t)⊤Γṽj(t)−ṽi(t)where j∈Ni, πij=πji>0 and cij(0)=cji(0)>0.

By introducing a dynamic threshold, the ET time sequence is determined by the condition (6)tk+1i=infl>tki{l:Hi(ei(t),ci(t),{ηˆij(t):j∈Ni})>δi(t),∀t∈(tki,l]}(i∈V) where k=1,2,… and δi(t) is an internal dynamic variable which evolves according to (7)δ̇i(t)=−αiδi(t)−μiγiHiei(t),ci(t),{ηˆij(t):j∈Ni}with αi>0, μi∈(0,1) and δi(0)>0.

Under the one-to-all ETC (6), a fully distributed and observer-based protocol is designed as (8)ui(t)=K∑j=1Naijcij(t)(ṽj(t)−ṽi(t))ṽi(t)=eA(t−tki)vi(tki)ċij(t)=πijaijṽj(t)−ṽi(t)⊤Γṽj(t)−ṽi(t)where t∈[tki,tk+1i), tki=max{tsi≤t:s∈N}, and vi(tki) is the transmitted signal of observer i at the latest triggering time tki before t. K∈Rm×n is the feedback gain matrix to be determined.

Remark 1

The so-called ADET strategy (6) includes two time-varying parameters: δi and ci. δi is a dynamic threshold, which is responsible for the dynamic part. In addition, ci is actually the row sum of the weighted adjacency matrix (aijcij)N×N, which is responsible for the adaptive part. The distributed updating law (5) of cij plays a key role in the full-distributed design of the ADET strategy (6).

Remark 2

The proposed ADET strategy (6) is general, which includes some commonly studied event conditions as special cases. For example, by letting ċi≡0 in (6), the ADET strategy (6) becomes to the case with constant coupling weights as discussed in Girard, 2015, He, Xu et al., 2020, Li et al., 2020 and Xu et al. (2019). In addition, some static ET schemes in Cheng and Li, 2019b, Hu et al., 2016, Li et al., 2015 and Xu et al. (2017), could be regarded as a special case of the ADET strategy (6) with δi(t)≡0.

3.2. ET consensus criteria under one-to-all ETC

We are in the position to analyze whether the observer-based consensus protocol (8) under one-to-all ETC (6) effectively solves the asymptotic consensus problem of the multi-agent system (1).

For convenience of analysis, let (9)ξi(t)=xi(t)−1N∑j=1Nxj(t),ηi(t)=vi(t)−1N∑j=1Nvj(t),χi(t)=ηi(t)−ξi(t),according to (1), (8), one has (10)ξ̇i(t)=Aξi(t)+Bui(t)η̇i(t)=Aηi(t)+Bui(t)+FC[ηi(t)−ξi(t)]χ̇i(t)=(A+FC)χi(t)for i=1,2,…,N. Furthermore, define ηij(t)=vi(t)−vj(t), η(t)=[η1⊤(t),η2⊤(t),…,ηN⊤(t)]⊤, and χ(t)=[χ1⊤(t),…,χN⊤(t)]⊤.

In order to determine gain matrices, we solve the following algebraic Riccati equations (AREs) (11)A⊤P+PA−PBB⊤P+In=0QA⊤+AQ−QC⊤CQ+In=0to get P>0 and Q>0. Then, let K=B⊤P, Γ=PBB⊤P and F=−12QC⊤.

Theorem 1 One-to-All ETC

Suppose that Assumption 1 holds and the matrices K, Γ and F are given in (11) and αi>1−μiγi in (6)–(7). Then, under the ADET strategy (6) and the observer-based consensus protocol (8), the general linear multi-agent system (1) achieves asymptotic consensus. Moreover, Zeno behavior is excluded.

Proof

See Appendix.

Remark 4

It is worthwhile to mention that the feedback gains K, F and the coupling gain Γ are designed in a node-based way, which are independent of any network information like the information of the network topology that is commonly used in the existing works (He, Xu et al., 2020, Hu et al., 2016, Xu et al., 2019). As such, the protocol ui in (8) is fully distributed, thereby exhibiting the merit of high scalability.

Remark 5

A dynamic threshold has been utilized in Du et al., 2018, He, Xu et al., 2020 and Li et al. (2020) for the ET function, where the triggering parameters are all constants. It is worth noting that the selection of these parameters typically depends on some global information. However, it follows from Theorem 1 that, for the ADET strategy (6), the parameters αi, μi and γi are designed in a node-based way, that is, the selection is independent of neighboring agents and the network topology. In addition, the time-varying parameter ci(t) in (6) is updated dynamically following the adaptive law (5), where the initial value ci(0)>0 can be arbitrarily chosen. This implies that the design of ci(t) does not involve any global information, which contributes to the full-distributed fashion of the ADET strategy (6).

4. The ADET strategy for one-to-one ETC

The last section provides a solution for a full-distributed observer-based consensus design based on one-to-all ET control (6), (8). This section goes further in this direction for a more flexible scheme — an asynchronous ETC (namely, one-to-one mode). Unlike one-to-all ETC in the above section, the one-to-one ETC allows one agent to asynchronously transmit its information to each of its neighbors, respectively, and is thus relatively flexible. A sufficient condition ensuring asymptotic consensus based on one-to-one ETC is derived and the exclusion of Zeno behavior is discussed in this section.

4.1. One-to-one ET controller

To characterize an one-to-one ETC, the triggering time sequence associated with an edge from agent i to agent j is introduced, i.e. 0≤t0i→j<t1i→j<⋯<tsi→j<⋯, which is obviously different from the one-to-all case.

The observer error from agent i to agent j corresponding to the asynchronous case is defined as eij(t)=ṽij(t)−vi(t),t∈[tki→j,tk+1i→j)where ṽij(t)=eA(t−tki→j)vi(tki→j). An ET function Hij(⋅,⋅,⋅):Rn×R×Rn→R is designed as follows (12)Hij(eij(t),cij(t),η̃ij(t))=γijcij(t)eij⊤(t)Γeij(t)−ιijη̃ij⊤(t)Γη̃ij(t)where η̃ij(t)=ṽij(t)−ṽji(t) and γij, ιij are given positive scalars and Γ∈Rn×n is a constant matrix to be determined. In addition, the coupling weight cij(t) is time-varying with the following updating law (13)ċij(t)=πijoṽji(t)−ṽij(t)⊤Γṽji(t)−ṽij(t)where πijo=πjio>0 and cij(0)=cji(0)>0. Obviously, cij(t)=cji(t) with t≥0 for (i,j)∈E and cij(t)≡0 for (i,j)∉E.

The asynchronous triggering sequence {tki→j}k∈N is determined by (14)tk+1i→j=infl>tki{l:Hij(eij(t),cij(t),η̃ij⊤(t))>δ̃ij(t),∀t∈(tki→j,l]},for ∀ i∈V,j∈Ni. Here, δ̃ij(t) denotes the dynamic threshold, which evolves according to (15)δ̃̇ij(t)=−α̃ijδ̃ij(t)−μ̃ijγijHij(eij(t),cij(t),η̃ij(t))with α̃ij>0, μ̃ij∈(0,1) and δ̃ij(0)>0. We refer to (14) as the ADET strategy for one-to-one ETC.

Under the one-to-one ETC, at instant tki→j, agent i transmits its information to only agent j, which makes it possible that tki→js≠tki→jq for js,jq∈Ni with js≠jq and k∈N. Thus, the one-to-one ETC leads to distinct information of one agent being transmitted to its neighbors.

Under the one-to-one ETC determined by (14), a fully distributed and observer-based protocol is developed as (16)ui(t)=K∑j=1Naijcij(t)ṽji(t)−ṽij(t)ṽij(t)=eA(t−tki→j)vi(tki→j)ċij(t)=πijoṽji(t)−ṽij(t)⊤Γṽji(t)−ṽij(t)where tki→j=max{tsi→j:tsi→j≤t}. It is easy to find ṽji(tkj→i)=vj(tkj→i). K∈Rm×n is the feedback gain matrix to be determined by (11). Due to asynchronous transmission under one-to-one ETC, ṽi in (8) is replaced by ṽij (j∈Ni) in (16).

Remark 6

Compared with the one-to-all ETC (6), the one-to-one ETC (14) introduces different triggering sequences {tki→j} (j∈Ni) for each agent i so as to efficiently adjust its transmissions to each of its neighbors j∈Ni, respectively. Under the one-to-one ETC, the involvement of different time scales in each agent’s transmissions does bring difficulties to the analysis of agents’ dynamics and asymptotic consensus. The next task is how to design a proper Lyapunov function to prove the effectiveness of the observer-based protocol (16).

4.2. ET consensus criteria under one-to-one ETC

Whether the consensus protocol (16) under one-to-one ETC (14) effectively solves the observer-based consensus problem of multi-agent system (1) in a fully distributed fashion is answered in this subsection.

Theorem 2 One-to-One ETC

Suppose that Assumption 1 holds and the matrices K, Γ and F are given in (11) and α̃ij>1−μ̃ijγij for (i,j)∈E in (14)–(15). Then, under the ADET strategy (14) and the observer-based consensus protocol (16), the multi-agent system (1) with general linear dynamics achieves asymptotic consensus. Moreover, Zeno behavior is excluded.

Proof

(i) In this part, we will prove that the asymptotic consensus can be achieved under the protocol (16) with the ADET strategy (14).

First, consider a function as (17)V(η(t),κ(t))=12∑i=1Nηi⊤(t)Pηi(t)+∑i=1N∑j=1Naij(cij(t)−α̃o)28πijo where κ(t)=[κ1⊤(t),…,κN⊤(t)]⊤ with κi(t)=[ci1(t),…,ciN(t)]⊤ (i∈V), P and πijo are defined in (11), (13), respectively. Here, α̃o is any positive constant satisfying α̃o>min1,4q̃0(1−4ι̃)λ2 where ι̃=max(i,j)∈E{ιij}, and the positive number q̃0 will be determined later. Then, by using (10), the derivative of V along the trajectory (1), (16) can be obtained as (18)V̇(η(t),κ(t))=12∑i=1Nηi⊤(t)(PA+A⊤P)ηi(t)−∑i=1Nηi⊤(t)PBK∑j=1Naijcij(t)η̃ij(t)+∑i=1N∑j=1Naijcij(t)−α̃o4η̃ij⊤(t)Γη̃ij(t)+∑i=1Nηi⊤(t)PFCχi(t). Note that ∑i=1Nηi⊤(t)Γ∑j=1Naijcij(t)η̃ij(t)=∑j=1Nηj⊤(t)Γ∑i=1Najicji(t)η̃ji(t)=−∑j=1Nηj⊤(t)PBK∑i=1Naijcij(t)η̃ij(t) where the second equation holds due to aij=aji, cij(t)=cji(t) and η̃ij(t)=−η̃ji(t) with t≥0. Thus, one can obtain (19)∑i=1N∑j=1Nηi⊤(t)PBKaijcij(t)η̃ij(t)=12∑i=1N∑j=1Naijcij(t)[ηi(t)−ηj(t)]⊤Γη̃ij(t) with K=B⊤P and Γ=PBB⊤P. Note that vi(t)=ṽij(t)−eij(t) and vj(t)=ṽji(t)−eji(t), and then it follows from ηi(t) in (9) that ηi(t)−ηj(t)=vi(t)−vj(t)=[ṽij(t)−eij(t)]−[ṽji(t)−eji(t)]. (ii) In this part, we prove by contradiction that there is no Zeno behavior. Assume that the triggering sequence {tki→j}k∈N generated by (14) exhibits the Zeno behavior, which implies that ∃T∗ij>0 s.t. limk→+∞tki→j=T∗ij. Since the right-hand sides of (1)–(2), (13), (15) are locally bounded, the variables {xi,vi,cij,δ̃ij} grow at most linearly on each bounded subset of its domain, and thus must be bounded in finite time. Then, it follows from Goebel et al. (2012, Proposition 6.10) that global existence of the solution is guaranteed. For ∀t∈[0,T∗ij], ∃cˆ1,B4,B5,B6,B7>0 s.t. |cij(t)|≤cˆ1, ‖δ̃ij(t)‖≤B4, ‖xi(t)‖≤B5, ‖vi(t)‖≤B6 and ‖η̃ij(t)‖≤B7, ∀ i,j=1,2,…,N.

Let ϱˆij be an upper bound of cˆ‖BK‖∑j=1Naij‖η̃ij(t)‖+‖FC‖(‖vi(t)‖+‖xi(t)‖) during t∈[0,T∗ij] and ιˆc=δij(0)γijcˆ1‖Γ‖exp{−12(α̃ij+μ̃ijγij)T∗ij} with α̃ij, μ̃ij, γij, δij(0) in (15) and Γ in (11).

On one hand, choose ɛ<ln‖A‖ιˆcϱˆij+1, ∃ N0′>0 s.t. tki→j∈[T∗ij−ɛ,T∗ij] for k≥N0′. On the other hand, according to (15)–(14), one has δ̃ij(t)≥δ̃ij(0)exp−α̃ij+μ̃ijγijt with t≥0.

One sufficient condition for the event condition (14) is ‖eij(t)‖2≤δ̃ij(0)exp−α̃ij+μ̃ijγijt/(γijcˆ1‖Γ‖). We recall eij(t)=ṽij(t)−vi(t). Note that eij is reset to zero and is not continuous at the triggering instants {tki→j}. Then, we calculate the right-hand Dini derivative of eij during [tki→j,tk+1i→j). It follows from (2), (16) that

D+eij(t)=Aeij(t)−BK∑j=1Naijcij(t)(ṽji(t)−ṽij(t))−F(Cvi(t)−Cxi(t)), which implies that D+‖eij(t)‖≤‖A‖‖eij(t)‖+ϱˆij. Define a function Φ(t) with (29)Φ̇(t)=‖A‖Φ(t)+ϱˆijwith Φ(0)=0. Obviously, ‖eij(t)‖≤Φ(t−tki→j) with Φ(t)=ϱˆij‖A‖exp{‖A‖t}−1. This implies that tk+1i→j−tki→j≥Δ and Δ is the time interval for Φ(t) evolving from 0 to ιˆc. It is easy to obtain Δ=ln‖A‖ιˆcϱˆij+1>0. This contradicts the assumption of tk+1i→j−tki→j≤ɛ<ln‖A‖ιˆcϱˆij+1=Δ. Therefore, there is no Zeno behavior.

Remark 7

The introduced dynamic variable δ̃ij(t) plays an essential role in the exclusion of Zeno behavior. When δ̃ij(t)≡0 (i.e., the static version), it is difficult to prove that the triggering sequence does not exhibit Zeno behavior. To address this problem, the commonly adopted strategy is to degrade the system performance from asymptotic consensus to bounded consensus (i.e., the consensus error is ultimately bounded) (Cheng and Li, 2019b, Ding et al., 2018, Wu et al., 2018). This paper is intended to exclude Zeno behavior without sacrificing the system performance, thus the dynamic variable δ̃ij(t) is well deigned in (15) and an ADET strategy is then developed for the one-to-one ETC (14). The similar analysis is also suitable for the dynamic variable δi(t) in (6).

Remark 8

The considered one-to-one ETC is different from most of existing ETC schemes, which releases the requirements for tki→j=tkj→i in the classical edge-based ETC (Cao et al., 2015, Xiao et al., 2012, Xu et al., 2017) and of tki→ji=tki→j2 (∀j1,j2∈Ni) in the classical node-based ETC (Dimarogonas et al., 2012, Meng and Chen, 2013). This implies that under one-to-one ETC, each agent is able to decide its own triggering instant tki→j without being constrained by any synchronous executions. In this regard, the one-to-one ETC is likely to have higher flexibility in adjusting information transmissions.

It should be emphasized that the developed framework is also suitable for the case where the full state of agents is available. In this scenario, the observer is no longer needed. Accordingly, vi and ṽij in (12)–(16) will be replaced with xi and x̃ij. Then a result for the state-feedback case is obtained in Corollary 1.

Assume that all states of agents are accessible, by replacing vi and ṽij in (12)–(16) with xi and x̃ij, the corresponding state-feedback ADET and consensus protocols are obtained, denoted as (11)′–(15)′.

Corollary 1

Suppose that Assumption 1 holds and the matrices K=B⊤P, Γ=PBB⊤P, P>0 is one solution of the following ARE (30)A⊤P+PA−PBB⊤P+I=0.and α̃ij>1−μ̃ijγij for (i,j)∈E in (13)′–(14)′. Then, under the ADET strategy (13)′ and the observer-based consensus protocol (15)′, the multi-agent system (1) with general linear dynamics achieves asymptotic consensus. Moreover, Zeno behavior is excluded.

Proof

The proof is similar with Theorem 2, and thus is omitted here.

Remark 9

To the best of our knowledge, there are very few work on one-to-one ETC. An asynchronous edge ETC strategy based on the full state feedback has been studied in Cheng and Li (2019a), where the proposed ETC strategy is static and bounded consensus is ensured. It is worth noting that the objective of this paper is to achieve asymptotic consensus, and thus the ETC strategy in Cheng and Li (2019a) is no longer applicable. In contrast, according to Corollary 1, our state-feedback consensus protocol (15)′ with the ADET strategy (13)′ can ensure asymptotic consensus as well as exclude Zeno behavior.

Remark 10

Compared with the existing ET laws (Cheng and Li, 2019b, Dimarogonas et al., 2012, He, Xu et al., 2020, Xu et al., 2017, Yi, Liu et al., 2019), this paper presents one of the first few attempts to tackle the fully distributed and observer-based consensus control under ETC for general linear multi-agent systems. Fully distributed nature (independent of any global information) leads to the main difficulty in designing the ET strategy and the consensus protocol. By adopting a dynamic event threshold and adaptive coupling weights, the fully distributed ADET strategy is established for one-to-all ETC and one-to-one ETC. Such adaptive coupling weights are also utilized in the consensus protocol, thereby contributing to the full-distributed fashion of consensus protocols based on the observers’ information. The derived results illustrate that the asymptotic consensus can be guaranteed, and the proposed ADET schemes and consensus protocols have high scalability and flexibility.

5.1. One-to-all ETC under the observer-based ADET strategy (6)

The one-to-all ETC is determined by the ADET strategy (6) with γi=0.5, ιi=1, αi=1, μi=0.6 in (4), (7) and πij=0.1 in (5). Under the one-to-all ETC, one agent always transmits its observation information to all of its neighbors, and hence only one triggering sequence is generated for each agent. Then, the generated triggering instants of transmission for agents 1−6 are displayed in Fig. 2 (left), and the total number of transmissions during the interval [0,10] for six agents are listed in Table 1. The evolutions of ci (∀i=1,…,6) are also shown in Fig. 2 (left). The adaptive parameters tend to be constants. The observer-based consensus protocol ui in (8) guarantees that states of all agents reach consensus, as shown in Fig. 2 (right).

5.2. One-to-one ETC under the observer-based ADET strategy (14)

The one-to-one ETC is determined by the ADET strategy (14) with γij=0.5, ιij=1, α̃ij=1 and μ̃ij=0.6 in (12), (15) and πijo=0.1 in (13). Under one-to-one ETC, one agent transmits its information to each of its neighbors, respectively, and thus different triggering sequences are generated from one agent to each of its neighbors, which is shown in Fig. 3. It is displayed in Fig. 3 and Table 1 gives the total number of transmissions generated during the interval [0,10] for six agents. In addition, the consensus protocol (16) effectively guarantees that the states of all agents tend to the same value eventually, and the coupling weights cij (∀(i,j)∈E) under (13) converge to constants.

5.3. Some comparisons

5.3.1. One-to-all vs. one-to-one ETC

Firstly, the comparison between one-to-all and one-to-one ETC with respect to the triggering number is provided in Table 1. Specially, for agent 1, the transmissions under the one-to-one ETC to its neighboring agents 2,3,4,6 are 29,28,26 and 38, respectively during [0,10], while under the one-to-all ETC, 42 is for agents 2,3,4 and 6. In this case, less transmissions are generated under the one-to-one ETC by the ADET strategy (14) for agent 1. A similar conclusion is also suitable for agents 3, 5 and 6. In contrast, for agents 2 and 4, the one-to-all ETC generates less triggers for transmission as compared with the one-to-one ETC. Therefore, the one-to-one and one-to-all ETC could be comparable in terms of the number of transmissions.

Table 1. The total number of triggers during [0,10] under one-to-all/one-to-one ADET strategies (6) and (14).

5.3.2. Dynamic vs. static ETC strategies

By letting δi≡0 in (6) and δ̃ij≡0 in (14), one has the static version following our ADET strategies (6), (14). Our strategies and the corresponding static ones are compared in Fig. 4 (left) for one-to-all and one-to-one ETC, respectively. Notice that δi>0 in (6) and δ̃ij>0 in (14). The dynamic ETS (with δi>0 or δ̃ij>0) is likely to provide a larger event threshold, as compared with the static one (i.e. δi=0 or δ̃ij=0), which is also displayed in Fig. 4 (left).

5.3.3. The discussion on γi and γij in ADET strategies

We discuss effects of the parameters γi in (4) and γij in (12) on the triggering frequency. Generally, a larger event threshold has the potential of keeping a slower triggering frequency. Here, we choose two different values for γi and γij, respectively, for one-to-all and one-to-one ETC. It can be found in Fig. 4 (right) that the case with γi=0.1 (or γij=0.1) provides a larger dynamic threshold for ‖ei‖ or (‖eij‖), as compared with that with γi=5 (or γij=5). This implies that the smaller the γi (γij) can be chosen, the slower the triggering frequency can be expected.

5.3.4. Comparison with the existing ET strategies

We further discuss the ET laws proposed in He, Xu et al. (2020) and Meng and Chen (2013) in this example. It can be seen from Fig. 5 that the ET law with periodic sampling in Meng and Chen (2013) and the dynamic ET law with fixed triggering constants in He, Xu et al. (2020) require more transmissions, while guaranteeing consensus.

6. Conclusions

This paper proposes a novel class of ADET strategies to solve the fully distributed consensus control problem of multi-agent systems with general linear dynamics under ETC. Firstly, an ADET strategy is developed for synchronous ETC, which introduces an internal variable as a dynamic threshold and adaptive triggering parameters associated with each node. Following this line, a flexible and reliable asynchronous ETC is proposed and the corresponding ADET strategy is developed. Under the proposed ADET strategy, fully distributed and observer-based consensus protocols are established for synchronous and asynchronous ETC, respectively, which not only guarantee asymptotic consensus, but also successfully eliminate Zeno behavior. Finally, a numerical example is provided to illustrate the effectiveness of the proposed ADET strategies and consensus protocols. Our future research topics would include the extensions to (1) leader-follower consensus issue; (2) more general graphs such as directed graphs or time-varying graphs; and (3) more general systems such as nonlinear or linear system with uncertainties/disturbances/noises by using more sophisticated consensus algorithms in Li et al., 2021, Wang et al., 2020, Yang et al., 2019a, Yang et al., 2019b.

Cited by (12)

  • Adaptive appointed-time formation tracking control for multiple spacecraft with collision avoidance under a dynamic event-triggered mechanism

    2022, Advances in Space Research

    This paper focuses on the appointed-time formation control problem for multiple spacecraft with limited communication and control resources. The control objective is to make each spacecraft move along its reference trajectory with guaranteed tracking performance while avoiding collision with each other. To this end, we attempt to propose an event-triggered formation tracking control protocol to achieve this objective. Firstly, a sliding mode manifold containing formation tracking and velocity errors is designed. Then, a group of prescribed performance constraints are imposed on the transient and steady-state behaviors of the newly defined sliding mode manifold, to derive a formation controller with performance guarantees and appointed-time convergence. By integrating the artificial potential function, a collision-free control term is devised, which is plus after the foregoing formation tracking controller to avoid the collision between the neighboring spacecraft. Furthermore, to reduce unnecessary data transmission and improve resource utilization, a dynamic event-triggered strategy is proposed to determine when the developed controller updates. In this case, the threshold parameter in triggering condition is dynamically changed over time rather than being fixed, in order to achieve a desired balance between communication frequency and system performance. Compared with the existing works, the major advantage of the proposed control protocol is that the formation tracking performance, the collision avoidance and the communication transmission preservation can be assured simultaneously. Finally, comparative simulations illustrate the effectiveness of the proposed protocol.

  • Distributed dynamic edge-based event-triggered formation control for multiple underactuated unmanned surface vessels

    2022, Ocean Engineering

    This paper investigates the distributed formation control problem for underactuated unmanned surface vessels (USVs) under communication resources constraints and unknown external disturbances. Based on the adaptive algorithm and the minimal learning parameter (MLP) algorithm, a distributed dynamic edge-based event-triggered controller is proposed to achieve the desired formation maneuver. Different from the node-based event-triggered strategy, the edge-based event-triggered mechanism in this paper is developed depends on the information of every edge. Besides, the internal dynamic variable is embedded in the triggering function to obtain larger triggered time interval. Only the triggered condition of every edge is reached can the communication happen, such that the communication burden will be effectively reduced. The theoretical result exhibits that the tracking errors will converge into a tiny region under this control scheme. Finally, numerical simulations are presented to demonstrate the validity of the proposed controller.

  • Dynamic event-triggered trajectory tracking control for underactuated marine surface vessels with positive minimum inter-event time guarantees

    2022, Ocean Engineering

    This paper proposes a dynamic event-triggered trajectory tracking control scheme for underactuated marine surface vessels (MSVs) with positive minimum inter-event time (MIET) guarantees. Under the presented scheme, control inputs only need to transmit to actuators at the designed event triggering time. Additionally, the maximum signal transmission frequency can be prior known by designers. To facilitate the design of the above control architecture, an unified second-ordered tracking error dynamic system is firstly derived. Then, based on the transformed error dynamic system, an event-based adaptive control law is developed. To counteract external disturbances and unmodeled dynamics, the minimum-learning-parameter (MLP) based neural approximator is constructed to enhance system robustness. Finally, by introducing internal dynamic variables, a dynamic event-triggered mechanism (DETM) is established to manage communications between the control module and actuators. Compared with existing event-triggered methods, the proposed event-driven method is dynamic and more flexible to satisfy network bandwidth requirements. Besides, MIETs of the presented DETM are also proved to be strictly positive and computable from control parameters. Theoretical analysis and simulation results verify the validity and effectiveness of the proposed DETM based control scheme.

  • Fully distributed quantized secure bipartite consensus control of nonlinear multiagent systems subject to denial-of-service attacks

    2022, Neurocomputing

    This paper is intended to solve the fully distributed secure bipartite consensus problem of nonlinear multi-agent systems (MASs) with quantized information under Denial-of-Service (DoS) attacks. The attacks, which constrained on attack frequency and duration are studied. Firstly, we propose a novel secure output feedback control protocol integrated of the logarithmic quantizer and relative output measurements of neighboring agents, which can realize secure control under DoS attacks by choosing the design parameters correctly. Secondly, an adaptive control protocol that includes dynamic coupling strengths into the control law and the state observer function is developed. Contrast to the single adaptive control strategy, two adaptive couplings constructed in sensor-to-observer, and controller-to-actuator channels, respectively, which can alleviate the burden of the limited bandwidth and energy consumption more effectively. Furthermore, this control strategy with dynamic coupling gains is fully distributed, under which agents are not required to know a priori knowledge of any global information and the quantizer only needs to quantize the output state error information of agents. Then, theoretical guarantees on the effectiveness of the proposed controllers in steering the system to a secure bipartite (bounded) consensus under quantized output measurements and intermittent DoS attacks are derived. Finally, the numerical simulation inspired by a real-world physical network system is developed to verify the usefulness of the presented controllers.

  • Neural-networks-based event-triggered consensus tracking control for nonlinear MASs with DoS attacks

    2022, Neurocomputing

    In this paper we explore the observer-based event-triggered tracking control problem for nonlinear multi-agent systems (MASs) under denial-of-service (DoS) attacks. To overcome the difficulty introduced by the nonlinear term, an observer based on neural networks (NNs-observer) is introduced to estimate unavailable system states. Besides, this paper designs a new secure distributed controller which can achieve the tracking control objective while maintaining the tolerance to DoS attacks. Furthermore, in order to save network resources, a new event-triggered mechanism is introduced which is mathematically proved to be free of the Zeno phenomenon. Finally, an example is provided to support the effectiveness of the proposed NNs-observer-based event-triggered resilient tracking control scheme.

  • Distributed robust event-triggered adaptive control for a class of uncertain nonlinear multi-agent systems with actuator saturation

    2022, Journal of the Franklin Institute

    This paper studies the event-triggered consensus control problem for high-order uncertain nonlinear multi-agent systems with actuator saturation. By using a smooth Lipschitz function to approximate the saturation nonlinearity, an augment system and the Nussbaum function are adopted to deal with the residual terms of saturation nonlinearity based on adaptive backstepping method. Since excessive energy and communication resources will be consumed during the procedure to handle actuator saturation, two event-triggered mechanisms are proposed to save the communication resources and reduce the controllers’ update frequency. Whenever the triggered conditions are satisfied, the control signals transmitted to the actuators are updated and broadcasted to the neighboring area. A ’disturbance-like’ term is integrated so that the event-triggered control problem with actuator saturation can be transformed into a robust problem while the unknown disturbances are tackled by adaptive update laws. Moreover, the requirement for global communication topology known by all the agents is relaxed by introducing new estimators. All the signals in the closed-loop system are uniformly bounded and the consensus tracking errors are exponentially converged to a bounded set. Meanwhile, the Zeno behavior is excluded. Simulation results are employed to validate the advantages of our proposed methods.
